{{Infobox newspaper | name = l'Alba | logo = | image = | caption = | type = Weekly | format = | owners = | founder = Giuseppe Colombo, R.A. Oliva | publisher = | editor = | chiefeditor = | assoceditor = | maneditor = | newseditor = | managingeditordesign = | campuseditor = | campuschief = | opeditor = | sportseditor = | photoeditor = | seniorstaff = | staff = | foundation = 5 September 1935 | political = Fascist | language = [[Italian language]] | ceased publication = 14 November 1935 | relaunched = | headquarters = [[Tunis]] | circulation = | sister newspapers = | ISSN = | oclc = | website = }} '''''L'Alba''''' was an [[Italian-language]] fascist weekly newspaper published from [[Tunis]], [[Tunisia]].<ref name="p2">''[https://books.google.com/books?id=IlnQAAAAMAAJ Nomenclature des journaux & revues en langue française du monde entier]''. Paris, Les bureaux de l'Argus, 1937. p. 467</ref><ref name="s2">Brondino, Michele. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=tbe-P46BE7AC&pg=PA199 La stampa italiana in Tunisia: storia e società, 1838-1956]''. Milano: Jaca Book, 1998. p. 199</ref><ref>''[https://books.google.com/books?id=D_4sAQAAIAAJ Africa: notiziario dell'Associazione fra le imprese italiane in Africa]'', Vol. 62. Associazione fra le imprese italiane in Africa, 2007. p. 452</ref> It was founded by Giuseppe Colombo and R. A. Oliva, with the first issue published on 5 September 1935.<ref name="p2"/><ref name="s2"/><ref name="m2">Bessis, Juliette. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=hJM5Dd2LwoIC&pg=PA173 La Méditerranée fasciste]''. 1981. p. 173</ref>
Regarding the [[Second Italo-Abyssinian War|war against Ethiopia]], ''l'Alba'' boasted of having two companies of [[blackshirts]] from Tunisia, "Numidie" and "Zama", at the battle-fields. The publication attacked [[freemasonry|freemasons]] and anti-fascists, while appealing to Italians to buy products from their own nation. The British consulate found the diatribes in ''l'Alba'' insulting to [[Great Britain]] and [[Malta]], and lodged a formal complaint against the publication. It was subsequently shut down by French colonial authorities - with the last issue published on 14 November 1935.<ref name="m2"/>
