== Legatum Institute ==

The [[Legatum Institute]], the publisher of the index, is a privately funded think-tank founded in 2007 and located in [[Mayfair]], [[London]].  It is funded by the private investment firm [[Legatum]], which includes Legatum Capital, a portfolio investment fund manager; Legatum Ventures a [[double bottom line]] investment fund, the Legatum Foundation, a philanthropic organisation; and the Legatum Center for Development And Entrepreneurship at Massachusetts Institute of Technology, a collaboration with MIT that funds graduate student entrepreneurs from developing markets.<ref name="australiahigh">[http://www.bruneidarussalam.embassy.gov.au/bnei/LegatumInstituteProsperityIndex.html Australian High Commission, "Australia Ranks First in Legatum Institute "Prosperity Index", Retrieved Apr. 3, 2009.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090514162728/http://www.bruneidarussalam.embassy.gov.au/bnei/LegatumInstituteProsperityIndex.html |date=2009-05-14 }}</ref>

=== Personnel ===

The Director of the Prosperity Index is the Danish economist [[Alexandra Mousavizadeh]]. The Prosperity Index is reviewed and critiqued by an advisory panel of academics and scholars representing a range of disciplines and includes: [[Tim Besley|Prof Tim Besley]] ([[London school of economics|London School of Economics]]); [[Daniel Drezner|Dr. Daniel Drezner]] ([[Tufts University]]); [[Carol Graham|Dr. Carol Graham]] ([[Brookings Institution]]); Dr. Edmund Malesky ([[University of California, San Diego]]); Dr. Ann Owen ([[Hamilton College (New York)|Hamilton College]]).

The Legatum Institute's International Advisory Group also contributes and assists in the Prosperity Index: Prof Peter Skerry ([[Boston college|Boston College]]); Prof Dan Chirot ([[University of Washington]]); Toby Mundy CEO ([[Atlantic Books]]); and Patrick Cheung.

