{{Expert-subject|Journalism|date=August 2011}} '''Operation Rubicon''' was a Scottish police investigation into allegations of [[phone hacking]], breach of [[Information privacy|data protection]] and [[Perjury#United Kingdom|perjury]].<ref name=StrathPol>>{{cite web|url=http://www.strathclyde.police.uk/index.asp?locID=1586&docID=8776|title=Statement published by Strathclyde Police|publisher=Strathclyde Police|date=July 2011|accessdate=2011-08-20|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924003230/http://www.strathclyde.police.uk/index.asp?locID=1586&docID=8776|archivedate=2011-09-24|df=}}</ref>
The operation was initiated by a complaint from [[Tommy Sheridan]]'s family solicitor, [[Aamer Anwar]], including allegations of perjury, phone hacking and breach of data protection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sdeeofof.moonfruit.com/download/i/mark_dl/u/4008566780/4550766590/22nd%20Jul%2711%20-%20Press%20Release%20by%20Aamer%20Anwar.pdf|title=Statement published by Aamer Anwar|publisher=Aamer Anwar|date=22 July 2011|accessdate=2011-08-20}}</ref>
The operation was a major investigation, led by [[Superintendent (police)#United Kingdom|Detective Superintendent]] John McSporran.<ref name=StrathPol/> ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]'' has reported that 50 officers are assigned to the case<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.met.police.uk/News/Man-arrested-in-connection-with-phone-hacking-and-corruption-allegations/1260269192692/1257246745756|title=Strathclyde force assigns 50 officers to phone-hack probe|publisher=Scottish Herald|date=18 August 2011|accessdate=2011-08-20}}</ref>
The investigation detained [[Andy Coulson]] on 30 May 2012<ref>{{Citation | title = Former News of the World editor Andy Coulson detained on perjury charges | place = | publisher = [[STV (TV network)|STV]] |date=May 2012 | url =http://local.stv.tv/glasgow/103888-former-news-of-the-world-editor-andy-coulson-arrested-on-perjury-charges/ }}</ref> and charged him with perjury.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/may/30/andy-coulson-charged-with-perjury</ref>
On 3 June 2015, Coulson was formally acquitted after a judge dismissed the case against him. All other cases investigated by Operation Rubicon were dropped without coming to trial.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carrell|first1=Severin|title=Andy Coulson cleared of perjury as Scottish court case collapses|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/jun/03/andy-coulson-cleared-of-perjury-in-scottish-court|accessdate=4 June 2015|publisher=The Guardian|date=3 June 2015}}</ref>
==Background== {{for|main article|HM Advocate v Sheridan and Sheridan}} {{Wikinews|Scottish politician going to jail after perjury conviction}}
On 16 December 2007, Sheridan was charged with perjury following a defamation case against the News of the World. On 23 December 2010, a jury found him guilty of perjury and on 26 January 2011 he was sentenced to 3 years in prison.
